<TITLE> Polish troops may train, not fight in Iraq-minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, Nov 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Poland may keep training Iraqi troops even if it withdraws from combat operations next year, Poland's new Defence Minister Bogdan Klich said on Monday. Poland's recently elected centre-right government of Prime Minister Donald Tusk has vowed to pull combat troops out of Iraq next year, contrary to their conservative predecessors who had considered a longer mission. "We can imagine a pullout of our combat troops next year but a Polish training mission under the NATO banner could stay there longer," Klich was quoted by daily Dziennik as saying. While NATO did not participate militarily in the 2003 US-led war in Iraq, it has been providing military training in the country. Poland, the largest ex-communist member of the 26-country NATO alliance, backed the 2003 US invasion of Iraq and still has 900 troops on the ground in the south of the country. Polish troops were initially supposed to end their mission this year, but the outgoing, staunchly pro-US conservatives had agreed to extend it to 2008 and possibly beyond. Tusk's Civic Platform party wants to refocus Polish foreign policy on its European Union partners, while promising to maintain close security cooperation with Washington. Klich said Poland would remain committed to NATO's military mission in Afghanistan, where it has over 1,000 soldiers. "With the view to Poland's credibility in NATO structures..., we should maintain the level of our presence in the coming years," he said. Doubts about the Polish mission in Afghanistan rose last week when prosecutors charged seven soldiers returning from duty there with intentionally killing Afghan civilia
